description:
Circle and dive into the sea! My first time witnessing an osprey fishing, and I had my camera on me. I had a manual focus lens on, but I had a couple of seconds while it was preparing to dive. Then, fell quickly and hit the water with a big splash. It seemed like it was under water for quite awhile, but according to the camera, it was only 2 seconds. Looks like no catch this time. It flew all the way to the island pictured after the attempt.

I was standing in a playground next to the seashore with maybe 20 other people around. I think I was the only one to notice this, as I looked around me afterwards. Quite an amazing experience to see!

In the 2 months following this, I've noticed 4 individual ospreys in the vicinity. Looking forward to capturing more from these beautiful birds.

description:
Group of 5 birds, 4 very small and fluffy and one larger bird—a Dunlin? see here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70138939

The plovers ran around and between each other, so I can't tell them apart. They are lumped in one observation.

The birds seemed to be a group, even flying off together, looping around a large circle and back to another part of the beach.

Are these plovers adult females? They show no rufus coloring on head and no black on the eye stripe or neck ring.

One Dunlin in a group of 4 Kentish Plovers on the beach.

Calidris alpina sakhalina? Observed in Japan, plumage is more plain grey and while, lacks any black on underparts.

Plovers in a separate observation:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70084345

description:
A Great Egret moves in too close to a Grey Heron . . .

The first photo is from the middle of the action scene.

The heron in more detail:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70495277

Same individual Great Egret here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70494875

A Grey Heron was fishing one day until a Great Egret decided to plop down right next door . . .

To see the Great Egret's reaction, see here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70494985

The Grey Heron wasn't bothered by the Little Egret, but it got in the way. Little Egret here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70495502

You can see the heron's crest rise in photo 1.

Little Egret was neighborly with a Grey Heron, until a Great Egret dropped in and the Grey Heron cleared the area.

The Great Egret's story here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70494985

The Grey Heron's here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70495277

This observation is for the male duck.

Female duck here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70495782

Egret here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70495782

This observation is for the female duck.

Male duck here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70495752

Egret here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70495502

A Grey Heron catches a minnow!

And then along comes a Great Egret:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70494985

You can see the heron's crest rise as it gets flustered here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70495277
